04036nam a22006135i 9780814789131DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t19971997nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147891317 a10.18574/97808147891312doi  a(DE-B1597)548487  a(OCoLC)782878098  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHV6439.U5Y 7aSOC0510002bisacsh04a364.106609731 aYablonsky, Lewis, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGangsters :b50 Years of Madness, Drugs, and Death on the Streets of America /cLewis Yablonsky. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[1997] 4cÂ©1997  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The current gang problem -- t2. Gangs in the twentieth century -- t3. Gang characteristics -- t4. Black and Chicano gangs: in and out of prison -- t5. Why gangs kill: the sociopath factor -- t6. Some effective interventions -- t7. The therapeutic community approach to gangs -- t8. Varied theoretical viewpoints -- t9. The violent gang as a near-group -- t10. Joining a positive gang: a plan for treating gangsters in a therapeutic community -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe effects of gang violence are witnessed every day on the streets, in the news, and on the movie screen. In all these forums, gangs of young adults are associated with drugs and violence. Yet what is it that prompts young people to participate in violent behavior? And what can be done to extract adolescents from the gangster world of crime, death, and incarceration once they have become involved? In Gangsters: 50 Years of Madness, Drugs, and Death on the Streets of America, Lewis Yablonsky provides answers to the most baffling and crucial questions regarding gangs. Using information gathered from over forty years of experience working with gang members and based on hundreds of personal interviews, many conducted in prisons and in gang neighborhoods, Yablonsky explores the pathology of the gangsters' apparent addiction to incarceration and death. Gangsters is divided into four parts, including a brief history of gangs, the characteristics of gangs, successful approaches for treating gangsters in prison and the community, and concluding with a review and analysis of notable behavioral and social scientific theories of gangs. While condemning their violent behavior in no uncertain terms, Yablonsky offers hope through his belief that, given a chance in an effective treatment program, youths trapped in violent behavior can change their lives in positive ways and, in turn, facilitate positive change in their communities and society at large.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aGangszUnited StatesxPrevention. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Violence in Society.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814789131423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814789131.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK